<DOC><DOCNO> AP890112-0241 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0736EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Pemex-At-A-Glance     01-12 0324</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Pemex-At-A-Glance,0339</SECOND><HEAD>Mexico's Government Petroleum Monopoly At A Glance</HEAD><BYLINE>With PM-Mexico-Union ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here is a look at Mexico's government petroleum monopolyPetroleos Mexicanos S.A., better known as Pemex, and the Oil WorkersUnion:</TEXT><TEXT>   THE COMPANY: Pemex is one of the biggest oil companies in theworld, accounts for nearly half the government's revenues and isintimately identified with the governing Institutional RevolutionaryParty.   It was created in 1938 after President Lazaro Cardenasnationalized foreign oil firms on March 18 of that year.   It is not a member of the oil cartel OPEC but tends to follow thepricing policies of the Organization of Petroleum ExportingCountries.</TEXT><TEXT>   ASSETS: By law, Pemex has a complete monopoly over theexploration and production of all hydrocarbons in Mexico, as well asrefining and the production of 36 ``basic'' petrochemicals. Itcontrols every aspect of the petroleum industry except for servicestations, which are private.   Pemex claims assets of $31 billion, including nine refineries anda score of petrochemical plants, as well as oil tankers, offshoredrilling rigs, one of the tallest buildings in the country and over32,000 miles of pipelines.</TEXT><TEXT>   PRODUCTION: Pemex is the world's sixth-largest producer of oiland the fifth-largest producer of petrochemicals.   Crude oil production is about 2.8 million barrels per day. Mexicois exporting about 1.36 million barrels a day, or about 40 percentof its oil, to 50 nations around the world. About half of theexports go to the United States.   Pemex supplies 90 percent of Mexico's energy needs.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE UNION: The Oil Workers Union controls more than half thelucrative drilling contracts let by Pemex and 95 percent of itsjobs. Pemex has about 180,000 employees and is consideredoverstaffed by industry experts.   Pemex workers are some of the highest paid in Mexico and enjoysome of the best fringe benefits. Jobs can be inherited and aresometimes sold under the table.</TEXT></DOC>